The paper is focused on performance analysis of benchmarks for neuroscience applications, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. The use of high-performance computing infrastructures also suggests that it could belong to the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category. The analysis of performance on different hardware architectures suggests that it could belong to the cs.CE (Computer Engineering) sub-category. The use of simulations and processing of experimental data sets suggests that it could belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories.
